AFL Player Roles Report

Tom Neill
2023-04-27

Do a quick Google search for ‘AFL positions’ and you will land you on a pretty standard image of a teams starting lineup: forwards, midfielders and defenders. Nothing wrong with that at all, but turn on a game of AFL and good luck picking out which player is in exactly which position.

Players are not exactly confined to their starting position. They all have different strengths and weaknesses, their team may play a different game style or they may get told to do different things by a different coach. Describing a player’s role from where they start each bounce down feels a bit like asking where someone’s office is rather than what job they do.

So, is it possible to use data to define player roles rather than positions? And importantly, is this actually a better way of describing players when compared to traditional positions?

Data

AFL is one of the most data rich sports in the world with hundreds of stats recorded every game. Everything from goals and disposals to one percenters and clangers. Unfortunately, most of this data is not open source.

Luckily for us Matthew Moyle maintains an AFL statistical database and provides a comprehensive API through the fitzRoy package in R. Thank you to Matthew for making this analysis possible.

“The fitzRoy package aims to provide a consistent and reliable API to various data sources of both the Men and Women competitions of the AFL. These functions provide easy and tidy access to data such as fixtures, results and statistics from various data sources.”

Analysis

Setup

This analysis uses a variety of R packages.

The data used in this project is from the 2022 AFL premiership season.

# create data frame of 2022 stats
raw_data_2022 <- fitzRoy::fetch_player_stats_fryzigg(2022)

Manipulating data

Now, there are a few things we need to do to get this data ready for analysis.

Firstly, there are some new metrics that we can create from existing ones: uncontested marks by subtracting contested marks from total marks for example. The more metrics we have, the more accurate our analysis can be.

On the other hand, there are some metrics that we don’t need. For example match information and Brownlow votes.

I’ve also decided to remove height and weight from this analysis. Height and weight are a common way to profile players. However, I want this analysis to be based on what a player does for their team, not their physical attributes: If a short player is good at marking or a tall player good at ground ball gets then that’s completely fine.

# creating new columns, selecting desired columns, grouping the data, filtering and standardising
data_2022 <- raw_data_2022 %>%
  mutate(
    uncontested_marks = marks - contested_marks, 
    marks_outside_fifty = marks - marks_inside_fifty, 
    tackles_outside_fifty = tackles - tackles_inside_fifty, 
    contest_def_wins = contest_def_one_on_ones - contest_def_losses, 
    contest_off_losses = contest_off_one_on_ones - contest_off_wins, 
    off_half_pressure_acts = pressure_acts - def_half_pressure_acts, 
    games_played = sum(is.numeric(player_id))) %>% 
  select(-1:-18, -22:-24, -26, -43, -53, -74, -79:-81) %>% 
  group_by(
    player_id, 
    player_first_name, 
    player_last_name, 
    player_team) %>% 
  summarise(across(c(1:55), mean), across(c(56), sum)) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>%
  filter(time_on_ground_percentage >= 50, games_played >= 10) %>%
  mutate(across(c(-1:-4, -10, -28:-29, -46, -60), function(x) (x/time_on_ground_percentage)*100)) %>% 
  mutate(across(c(-1:-4, -10, -28:-29, -46, -60), function(x) round((x-mean(c(x)))/sd(c(x)), digits = 5)))

After all this manipulation we can double check that our data set is clean and ready for analysis.

# final cleaning check
anyDuplicated(data_2022)
[1] 0
which(is.na(data_2022))
integer(0)

Broad roles

So time for the fun part, analysing our data. We have identified 51 stats for each player across the season and we want to see who is similar to who.

We can do this using UMAP, a dimension reduction algorithm. This algorithm reduces our 51 variables into two dimensions, allowing us to visualise the data. Which, as it turns out, is quite useful. Each data point is a player and players with similar stats will be closer in proximity.

# creating new data frame with relevant metrics for general mapping, umap
umap_data_2022 <- data_2022 %>% 
  select(-1:-4, -10, -28:-29, -46, -60) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(data_2022, .)

So what does this visualisation show us? Well if every player, aka data point, was the exact same then we would have one dot. Luckily that’s not the case. We also don’t just have three dots for traditional positions; forwards, midfielders and defence.

What we do have is a nice spread of data points with smaller groups or clusters. Every player is unique, which is exactly what we are trying to show, but there are certainly some clusters that indicate similarities.

Rather than subjectively deciding which point fit’s in which group, we can use a clustering algorithm, PAM in this case. This algorithm will automatically identify and name clusters in our data. Using an algorithm removes subjectivity, increases efficiency and leads to more accurate results.

# pam the dataset, add it to the dataset, rename column and values
broad_position_2022 <- umap_data_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 5) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_data_2022) %>% 
  rename(broad_position = ".") %>% 
  mutate(broad_position = 
           ifelse(broad_position == 1, "Forwards", 
                  ifelse(broad_position == 2, "On-ballers", 
                         ifelse(broad_position == 3, "Rucks", 
                                ifelse(broad_position == 4, "Connectors", 
                                       ifelse(broad_position == 5, "Defenders", broad_position)))))) %>% 
  mutate(broad_position = factor(broad_position, levels = broad_position_custom_order))

The algorithm has identified five clusters that we have subsequently named: forwards, on ballers, connectors, rucks and defenders.

So while our traditional forwards, defenders and rucks stay the same, we now have on ballers and connectors.

Let’s see how many players there are in each role and discuss what their top attributes are.

Rucks are a rare breed, coming in with the least number of players. The big men of the competition top the charts in hitouts, ruck contests and hitouts to advantage. No surprises there. The reason they are so far away from our other data points in their own cluster is because these metrics are so specific to their role. Unlike metrics shared by all, such as handballs, a ruck men may get fifty hitouts a game while a small forward will have 0 for the season.

The defenders cluster captures the last line of defence. These are players who are good at contested defensive one on ones, contested defensive wins, spoils and one percenters. Not often in the limelight defenders are a key part of their respective teams.

On ballers are the stars of the comp. Not a surprise when they are always in and around the ball. Whether that’s in the centre square for bounce down or at stoppages around the ground they excel at clearances, centre clearances, contested possessions and stoppage clearances

Forwards are responsible for some of the most highlight worthy moments in our game. From taking big marks or kicking bags to snapping goals from impossible angles. These guys are classified by shots at goal, goals, marks inside fifty and marks on lead.

Interestingly, connectors have the largest number of players. Connectors rank highly in uncontested marks, rebounds, marks outside fifty, effective kicks and intercepts.

As we can see from the visual they essentially sit in the middle of forwards, defenders and on ballers. This distinction is the first key insight of this analysis. Rather than having player positions grouped by three sections of the field we have a distinction between three key positions and connectors.

I think this is a really good way of watching and understanding the game. The key positions of forwards and defenders at each end of the ground and on ballers following the ball are glued together by connectors. Just as they are on the plot.

To double check our analysis we can check out how each team breaks down. We can see a very nice balance within each team, perfect.

Specific roles

So while making that distinction between key positions and connectors is an important insight, let’s take it a step further. Can we find even more specific roles within our broad positions?

Let’s start by splitting our data set into each broad role and apply our dimension reduction algorithm again to each subset. This allows us to compare players in each broad position between each other, replicating our analysis within each one.

# split combined data set into broad roles
broad_position_2022_list <- broad_position_2022 %>% 
  rename(X3 = X1, X4 = X2) %>% 
  split(., .$broad_position)
# re selecting relevant columns
umap_forwards_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Forwards %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Forwards)
umap_on_ballers_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$`On-ballers` %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$`On-ballers`)
umap_connectors_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Connectors %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Connectors)
umap_defenders_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Defenders %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Defenders)
umap_rucks_2022 <- broad_position_2022_list$Rucks %>% 
  select(-1:-5, -11, -29:-30, -47, -61:-63) %>% 
  umap() %>% 
  .$layout %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., broad_position_2022_list$Rucks)

We certainly have a spread of data points in each of our broad positions. Just like before this shows that each player is unique but again we have some clusters.

Lets apply our clustering algorithm to each of our broad roles and see what we can find.

# pam the broad roles
master_forwards_2022 <- umap_forwards_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 3) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_forwards_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Full-forward", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Playmaker", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Goal-sneak", specific_role))))
master_on_ballers_2022 <- umap_on_ballers_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 3) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_on_ballers_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Elite", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Enforcer", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Extractor", specific_role))))
master_connectors_2022 <- umap_connectors_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 4) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_connectors_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Quarter-back", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Orchestrator", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Impact",
                                ifelse(specific_role == 4, "Support", specific_role)))))
master_defenders_2022 <- umap_defenders_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 3) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_defenders_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Reliable", 
                  ifelse(specific_role == 2, "Aggressive", 
                         ifelse(specific_role == 3, "Full-back", specific_role))))
master_rucks_2022 <- umap_rucks_2022 %>% 
  select(X1, X2) %>% 
  pam(., k = 1) %>% 
  .$clustering %>% 
  data.frame() %>% 
  cbind(., umap_rucks_2022) %>% 
  rename(specific_role = ".") %>% 
  mutate(specific_role = 
           ifelse(specific_role == 1, "Ruckmen", specific_role))

Each of our broad positions have been broken down into a set of roles. We can see them clustered on our original visualisation.

And a nice distribution within the broad roles.

Let’s check each of them out.

The one broad role we don’t find any specific positions in is our ruck men. Unfortunately there just isn’t enough ruck men to identify any groupings or trends. Each ruck men will have their own unique strengths and weaknesses: Toby Nankervis of Richmond picks up disposals like a connector, Darcy Cameron boots goals like a forward, Mark Blicavs plays tackles like an on baller and Tim English helps his defence out with intercepts and rebounds.

Clustering ruck men would lead to inaccurate results… Each player is unique and applies their own skill set in their unique team setup.

Defenders have been broken down into three roles; aggressive, reliable and full back.

Coming up with a creative name for full backs was just not needed. The key pillar for a functioning defence these gups are tasked with shutting down the opponents most important forward. Think of Steven May, Darcy Moore, Jacob Weitering, Sam Taylor and Jeremy McGovern. Their key metrics include intercept marks, contested defensive wins and spoils. We also see guys like Jeremy Howe, Tom Barrass and Jordan Ridley in this category. Often playing as the second tall defender in their team these high quality players are elite in aerial situations.

The reliable defender, a team mate’s teammate. These guys rarely find themselves anywhere near a Brownlow vote but bet your bottom dollar the coach loves them. We are talking top of defensive one on one wins, spoils and one percenters. While they lack the aerial prowess of a full back these guys are some of the most consistent and hard working players in the comp. Think of Dylan Grimes, Jordan Butts, Harrison Petty or Tom McCartin.

Aggressive defenders… this is a nice way of describing the bloke who just did the thing that made you say “what the hell was that”. Pure chaos and entertainment these defenders do some of the craziest, dumbest and most impressive things on a footy field. If the ball goes near them make sure you are watching, they see the game like no other. Think of Sam Frost, Darcy Gardiner, Dane Rampe, Noah Balta or Tom Jonas. Their top metrics include defensive one on one losses, one percenters and spoils. Unfortunately this specific role also includes young players still developing to the level and players who just didn’t have their best season.

On ballers are some of the biggest names in the sport. AFLs most prestigious individual award, the Brownlow medal, almost always goes to an on baller. Our three on baller roles are elite, extractor and enforcer.

Extractors win the ball for their team at ground level in highly congested situations, distributing it out to other team mates. Think Joel Selwood, Travis Boak, Tom Liberatore and Jack Viney. Their top metrics include contested possessions, handballs and clearances. Their tough as nails, win at all costs attitude often makes them captain material. We also see some big names like Sam Walsh, Touk Miller, Clayton Oliver and Patrick Cripps fall into this category. Guys that have the ability to be elite. They may have to play a more extractor style role for a weaker side, be in a team whose focus is on contested possession or contribute elsewhere but are just really damn good at it.

Speaking of elites, these blokes can do it all. Calling them a swiss army knife makes it sound they are all right at everything, these guys are the dominant on ballers of the competition. Inside fifties, centre clearances, stoppage clearances, ground ball gets, contested possessions, tackles they can do it all. Andy Brayshaw, Marcus Bontempelli, Jack Steele, Christian Petracca, Callum Mills, you get the idea. These guys are the elites of their respective on ballers and team and are genuine stars of the competition.

Finally we have enforcers, tackles and pressure acts are the aim of the game here. These players are tough inside bulls who bring the contest. Think of Tom Atkins, Connor Nash, Hugh Greenwood and James Harmes. Similar to the aggressor role for defenders; it also represents taggers, young mids and players who just didn’t get their hands on the ball much and are forced to pressure and tackle opponents on ballers.

So let’s talk about the all important connectors. They have been split into four roles; support, impact, orchestrator and quarterback.

Quarterbacks are exactly who you think of; Shannon Hurn, Sam Docherty, Jake Lloyd, Jake Sinclair, James Sicily and Tom Stewart. Top for effective kicks, rebounds and metres gained these guys are some of the best kicks in the game and are tasked with launching attacks from the back.

Orchestrators are our outsider users. They are going to find space in the middle of the park and make the most of it. Top for uncontested possessions, uncontested marks, and metres gained. Think of Steele Sidebottom, Isaac Smith, Liam Bakar, Ed Langdon, Lachie Hunter and Josh Daicos. You will find these guys receiving the ball from quarter backs or on ballers to generate transitional ball movement through the centre of the ground.

Impact players are one of the more interesting roles to come out of this analysis. Their top attributes include pressure acts, tackles outside the fifty, contested marks, score involvements, one percenters and clangers. Quite the mix! These guys pop up when you least expect it, whether it’s making a crucial goal saving tackle in defence or slotting a clutch goal. Think of Jed Bews, Tom Powell, Bailey Williams, Mark O’Connor and Sam Durham. In reality a lot of players in this category are players still developing or aren’t quite being deployed in the role that suit’s them best. They may not be in a role where they get a lot of the ball, they can produce important moments for their team.

Last but not least, supports. Whether it’s sweeping up a loose attack or providing a marking option in transition these guys are there for their teammates when they need it. Their key metrics include intercepts, rebounds, marks and defensive one on one wins. Picture Jimmy Webster, Brayden Maynard, Jake Bowey, Blake Hardwick, Trent Rivers, John Noble, Zach Guthrie or Nathan Broad. A helping hand in both the defence and ball movement.

Finally we have forwards split up into full forwards, goal sneaks and playmakers.

Playmakers are the front half quarterback if you will, the number 10. They stitch together the work of connectors with the other forwards. Think of Nick Holman, Dylan Moore, Gryan Miers, Charlie Spargo, Zac Bailey, Beau McCreery, or Sam Powell-Pepper. These guys excel at goal assists, forward 50 ground ball gets, tackles inside fifty, offensive half pressure acts and marks on a lead. They will find the ball on the ground or in the air near the fifty metre line and find a target inside fifty.

Goal sneaks are your typical small forwards, think of Izak Rankine, Kysiah Pickett, Sam Switkowski, Tyson Stengle or Tom Papley. They are the definition of pest but all class with the ball. Tackles inside fifty, forward fifty ground ball gets, offensive half pressure acts, shots at goal and goals. They find a sneaky avenue to goal whether that’s picking the pocket of a defender or sweeping up scraps left by a full forward.

Speaking of, the jewel in a successful team’s crown; full forwards are one of the most captivating roles on the field. Offensive one on ones, marks inside fifty, marks on a lead and goals, a full forward on his day is a site to behold. Ask for someone to name an AFL player and they will probably say a full forward. Lance Franklin, Josh Kennedy, Tom Hawkins, Taylor Walker, Charlie Dixon, Tom Lynch, Charlie Curnow or Aaron Naughton. Similar to our full back role, we also see midsize marking forwards in this role. Players like Jack Riewoldt, Jack Gunston, Toby Greene and Jamarra Ugle-Hagan. These guys profile very similar to a full forward, elite in the air and at kicking goals, but often play as the second tall in their team.

Concluding thoughts

So, is it possible to define player roles using data player roles rather than positions? Absolutely. Is this actually a better way of describing players when compared to traditional positions?… probably not. The player roles identified actually line up pretty accurately with specific existing player positions:

  • Full backs at full-back and centre half-back

  • Aggressive and reliable defenders in the back pocket

  • Quarterbacks and supports across half back

  • Ruck men at ruck

  • Elite, enforcer and extractor at centre, rover and ruck-rover

  • Orchestrators on the wings

  • Connectors and impact players at half forward

  • Full forwards at full-forward and centre half-forward

  • Goal sneaks in the forward pocket

Can the analysis be used to understand player roles though? Absolutely. This analysis has helped deepen my understanding of player roles and the skill-sets they need. Similar analysis and classification could certainly be used on, say, the AFLs website, to describe different players. It could also present a way of measuring a player’s impact on a game not just by pure numbers, but by how well they are performing a role for their team.

I also think the idea of viewing player’s broad roles as ‘key’ positions and connectors is a great way to look at, watch, and understand the game. While obvious in hindsight, the traditional player map paints more of a picture of three separate areas.

This type of analysis could also be useful across AFL fantasy games which rely heavily on identifying and understanding player roles. We can certainly see trends across AFL Fantasy scoring and specific roles. Elites, extractors and quarterbacks often the most targeted roles come out on top as expected.

How could this analysis be improved or continued?

Those with access to even more comprehensive data could obviously conduct more accurate analysis. In addition, other mapping and clustering algorithms could be tested to see if results differ.

To continue the analysis you could also investigate:

  • What is each team’s most common lineup throughout the year? What are the specific roles of these players? How do they compare?

  • What do previous seasons of data look like?

  • Do player’s roles evolve over their careers?

  • Could you classify players after just a few games of data in a new season using previous season qualifications to see what role they are playing?

  • With player roles changing throughout a season how could you measure periods of time where players have a different role?

  • Could you combine player heat maps to create a visualisation of where each specific role spends most of their time?
